Mines.

A mine is a single-use planted explosive that detonates on whatever steps onto it. Unlike a spike or a force field that sits permanently dangerous, a mine has to be armed before it does anything, and once it goes off it's gone — a mine is a one-shot. That cuts both ways: it can be a buried trap waiting under the player's feet, or a weapon the player arms themselves and lures an enemy onto. Whatever sets it off — the player, an enemy, or a breakable object sharing its tile — takes the blast.

How a mine works.

A mine sits on a single tile. Before it's armed it's harmless, playing only its quiet spawn cue so it can be found. A mine becomes armed in one of two ways: it can be set to arm itself the moment the map loads, or the player can arm it by hand. To arm one by hand, stand on a tile directly beside the mine — not on top of it — and press enter; the mine lights and begins its ticking loop. Trying to arm a mine while standing right on top of it just warns the player to step to the side first, since arming it underfoot would blow them up.

Once armed, the mine waits. The next thing to enter its tile triggers the explosion: it plays its blast, deals its damage to whatever set it off, and is removed from the map. A player caught in the blast loses health reduced by their defence, or has the hit absorbed by a raised shield. An enemy that wanders onto an armed mine takes the damage instead, which is what lets the player use a mine offensively. An armed mine sharing its tile with a breakable object — a sign, clock, calendar, door, item, vehicle, destroyable spike, or destroyable wall — blows that object up as well. On 3d maps the mine sits at its given height and only triggers on that height.

Mine fields.

The mine form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the tile the mine is buried on.

Maximum attack. The damage the explosion deals to whatever sets the mine off, before defence is subtracted.

Mine sound (a folder name from the mine sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the spawn cue, the lit and ticking loop, and the explosion. Pick none for a silent mine.

Auto activate (checkbox). When checked, the mine arms itself the moment the map loads; when unchecked, it stays dormant until the player arms it from an adjacent tile.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the mine sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the highlighted theme's spawn cue, hold control and press L to hear its ticking loop, and hold control and press H to hear its explosion.

Authoring mines by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a mine is written under the name mine: mine x y damage minetype triggered. On 3d maps a z follows the y: mine x y z damage minetype triggered. The damage is a number, triggered is the literal word true for a mine that arms itself on load or false for one the player has to arm, and the mine sound must match a mine sounds folder name or the word none.
